{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"171b6a3b-0219-401b-be0c-25f462f1b60c","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. Add a `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n`EnableMSTestRunner` activates the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner built into MSTest 3.8.0. `OutputType Exe` is required since each test project becomes a self-contained executable.\n\n## 2. Add TRX report package to each test project\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n```\n\nOr add it once in a `Directory.Packages.props` / shared `.props` import.\n\n## 3. CI command\n\nOn **.NET 8 SDK**, `dotnet test` automatically bridges to MTP projects via the VSTest compatibility layer, so this still works:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --logger trx\n```\n\nNo change needed to the CI command — the bridge handles it transparently.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of per-project changes:** only the new `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package reference. Everything else is centralized in `Directory.Build.props`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60f398a5-16dd-4320-86fb-3fa2e2c7a286","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). They're on .NET 8 SDK and use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI.\n\nLet me provide a concise but complete answer about the migration steps.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Per-project or Directory.Build.props** - Set `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to enable the MTP runner.\n\n2. **For consistent properties across all projects**, use a `Directory.Build.props` file.\n\n\n3. **TRX logging** - With MSTest 3.8.0, the TRX logger is built-in, so `dotnet test --logger trx` should work as-is, though I should verify if `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` is needed separately.\n4. **CI command** - The `dotnet test` command remains largely the same, though the logger syntax might need adjustment depending on how MTP handles it.\n\nActually, I need to clarify the .NET 8 SDK behavior here. When using `dotnet test` with MTP-enabled projects, there's a compatibility layer at play—VSTest is still the default runner, but it bridges to MTP projects. The `--logger trx` flag might still work through that compatibility, but the native MTP approach could be different. Let me think through exactly how this works with .NET 8.\n\nThe cleanest setup would be to define the shared properties in `Directory.Build.props`, add the TRX reporting package to each test project, and then use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI, which should work via the VSTest bridge. Though with .NET 9 SDK, `dotnet test` got native MTP integration, so the behavior differs between versions.\n\nSetting up the Directory.Build.props file... Setting up the project file with the output type as an executable, then adding the TRX reporting package for test result logging. With .NET 8 SDK, the VSTest compatibility layer automatically handles `dotnet test --logger trx` even though the project uses the native test runner, so the CI command continues to work without needing to upgrade to .NET 9 or run executables directly.","outputTokens":1434,"requestId":"E3D8:229C6C:159A4A3:18363A8:6A051FA9"},"id":"37d1e250-d274-49c0-8050-dd3fe15f056f","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:05:07.328Z","parentId":"1681f3af-c549-419b-aaee-13543dc09c8e"}
